Exploratory Data Analysis and Findings

Bivariate Analysis

TableÂ 1 summarizes mean, median, standard deviation, minimum, and maximum prices for Airbnb listings1 across ten cities. The mean price varies widely, with cities like Cape Town (2405.12) and Bangkok (2078.28) exhibiting significantly higher averages compared to cities like New York (142.84) and Paris (113.10). However, the large standard deviations in cities such as Cape Town (6143.19) and Bangkok (6379.79) indicate high variability, likely influenced by luxury listings or extreme outliers. Conversely, cities like Paris (214.43) and New York (275.74) display smaller standard deviations, suggesting more consistent pricing across listings. Median prices, which are less sensitive to outliers, highlight that cities like Paris and New York predominantly cater to budget and mid-range accommodations, with median prices at 80 and 99, respectively.

1Â This dataset was sourced from Maven Analytics, accessed on November 3rd, 2024.

FigureÂ 1 plot complements this summary by visually highlighting price disparities and outliers. Cities like Cape Town, Bangkok, and Mexico City show extreme outliers, with maximum prices reaching 300,000 or higher, indicating the presence of high-end luxury properties. These outliers significantly inflate the mean price in these cities, as seen in TableÂ 1. On the other hand, cities like Paris, Rome, and New York exhibit compact distributions with fewer visible outliers, reflecting more standardized pricing. Additionally, cities like Rio de Janeiro and Istanbul also show significant variability in prices, but the lower median prices suggest that the majority of listings fall into affordable or mid-range categories.

Multivariate Analysis

TableÂ 2 provides a detailed overview of the correlations between price and numerical features such as accommodates, bedrooms, and minimum_nights for each city. Accommodates shows a significant positive correlation with price in cities like Cape Town (0.39) and Sydney (0.37), indicating that listings accommodating more guests generally have higher prices in these cities. Bedrooms also demonstrates strong positive correlations with price in Sydney (0.39) and Cape Town (0.36), suggesting that larger properties with more bedrooms command premium pricing in these markets. Minimum_nights exhibits weak correlations with price across all cities, with the highest correlation observed in Sydney (0.03). This suggests that the required minimum stay duration has minimal influence on pricing. Some cities, such as Hong Kong (-0.02) and Rome (-0.005), even show slightly negative correlations for minimum_nights, reinforcing its limited impact on price.

Darker shades in the FigureÂ 2 signify stronger correlations, such as the relationships between accommodates and bedrooms with price in cities like Sydney and Cape Town, where larger properties consistently command higher prices. Conversely, lighter shades denote weaker correlations, particularly for minimum_nights, which appears to have a negligible influence on pricing across all cities.

Overall, Cape Town and Sydney exhibit the strongest overall correlations between price and both accommodates and bedrooms, indicating that property size and capacity are key determinants of pricing in these cities. Accommodates consistently has the highest correlation with price across most cities, followed by bedrooms, reflecting the importance of property size in determining Airbnb prices. Minimum_nights consistently demonstrates weak correlations across all cities, indicating that its impact on pricing is minimal and possibly influenced by local market regulations or norms.

Progress Summary and Self-Assessment

In this stage of the project, I focused on preparing the dataset for analysis by transforming key variables and addressing challenges related to the data structure. First, I converted multiple columns into factors to enable categorical analysis, including variables such as host_response_time, neighbourhood, district, city, property_type, room_type, and review-related metrics (e.g., review_scores_rating, review_scores_accuracy, and others). This transformation ensures that these variables are appropriately handled in subsequent visualizations and statistical analyses.

In terms of analysis, I opted to compare prices within the same city to maintain consistency and avoid complications stemming from variations in local currencies. This approach allowed me to conduct meaningful bivariate and multivariate analyses, exploring the relationships between price and variables such as accommodates, bedrooms, and minimum_nights. To enhance the visualization of price distributions, I implemented a for loop to generate individual histograms for each city, which allowed me to observe and compare the unique price distributions across various markets effectively.

Additionally, as part of data tidying, I encountered the limitation that the main dataset (data/listings.csv) was 151.15 MB, exceeding GitHubâs file size limit of 100.00 MB. To address this, I decided to ignore this file in version control and focus on processing and analyzing it locally, ensuring efficient handling of the large dataset while maintaining a clean and manageable repository.

I am confident in my progress and fully expect to complete a thorough analysis by the end of the quarter.

Future Directions

I experienced a crash in R while attempting to pivot the amenities column, originally stored as a single text field with comma-separated values. My goal was to split these amenities into individual items, clean and standardize their labels, and transform them into separate columns using a pivot operation, where each amenity would be represented as a binary variable (TRUE/FALSE). This approach would enable a more granular analysis of the relationship between amenities and price. To prevent further crashes, I plan to divide the dataset by city, thereby reducing its size and improving runtime efficiency.

For the next stage of the analysis, I plan to focus on the top three cities with the highest number of listings: Paris, New York, and Sydney. Using geospatial data (latitude and longitude), I will create detailed maps for these cities to explore the relationship between location and pricing. This analysis aims to identify which areas within these cities exhibit the highest price tendencies, shedding light on premium neighborhoods that may appeal to travelers seeking luxury accommodations. Additionally, I will investigate the distribution of property_type and room_type across neighborhoods, determining whether certain types of housing (ex. âEntire placeâ or âPrivate roomâ) are concentrated in specific locations. By visualizing these patterns, I aim to uncover spatial trends in housing types and their impact on pricing within these cities.

In addition to geospatial analysis, I plan to incorporate review and amenity data into the current multivariable analysis. Once the amenities list column is properly pivoted, I will explore how customer reviews influence pricing by including review-related variables such as review_scores_rating, review_scores_accuracy, review_scores_cleanliness, review_scores_checkin, review_scores_communication, review_scores_location, and review_scores_value. This step will allow me to determine whether higher review scores correlate with higher prices and to identify which aspects of customer satisfaction (e.g., cleanliness, communication, or location) have the strongest influence on pricing. With the review data already converted to factors, this step is ready for implementation and will add a valuable dimension to the analysis.
